Cyclistic Bikes Analysis

Todd Wood

2023-04-28

Ask

How Do Annual Members and Casual Riders use Cyclistic Bikes differently?

We need to find the different ways that Casual Riders and Annual Members use Cyclistic Bikes. Those answers will be found using RStudio and the previous twelve months of bike share data for the City of Chicago.

Annual Member: User who purchases an annual pass for Cyclistic Bike Share services, a subscriber.

Casual Rider: User who purchases on a “by day” or “by ride” basis, a non-subscriber

We will identify trends in ridership by membership status according to:

  • type of bike

  • start time

  • day of the week

  • month

  • start station

Using:

  • number of rides

  • average ride times

Results will be delivered to Lily Moreno. Findings will be combined with the rest of the team to deliver a detailed report and plan to the Cyclistic Executive Team.

Hypothesis

Annual Members are expected to use the service most often compared to Casual Riders. Annual Members’ rides will most likely be used non-recreationally and their use will remain fairly consistent year-round.

Casual Riders are expected to use the service the least. Their use will most likely be recreational, for example riding for entertainment or sight seeing. Their use will depend more on time of day, day of week, and to the largest extent the time of year.

Prepare

Loading the tidyverse

#Prepare Rstudio for the import and analysis of the divvy-bikes monthly data sets by loading the tidyverse suite of packages
#Load scales package for y axis interpretation of large numbers
library(tidyverse)
options(scipen = 999)
library(scales)

Loading and testing our data sets

#Reading monthly bike data from April 2022 to March 2023 in RStudio for manipulation and analysis
#Assign them to objects for easier manipulation later
apr <- read_csv("202204-divvy-tripdata.csv")

jul <- read_csv("202207-divvy-tripdata.csv")
aug <- read_csv("202208-divvy-tripdata.csv")

oct <- read_csv("202210-divvy-tripdata.csv")
nov <- read_csv("202211-divvy-tripdata.csv")
dec <- read_csv("202212-divvy-tripdata.csv")
jan <- read_csv("202301-divvy-tripdata.csv")
feb <- read_csv("202302-divvy-tripdata.csv")
mar <- read_csv("202303-divvy-tripdata.csv")

These are Cyclistic bike share data for the previous twelve months of bike use in the City of Chicago. The data were generated, collected and stored by Cyclistic. Our users’ privacy is secure as their personal information is not included in the data sets.We can only infer the purchase of “single rides” or “day pass” for Casual Riders as that info is not included in the data set.

We will need to check them for consistent structure and data formats before we can combine them.

We will aggregate the 12 monthly frames into one yearly frame.

#Combine frames into one yearly frame
year <- bind_rows(apr,may,jun,jul,aug,sep,oct,nov,dec,jan,feb,mar)

##Process #### Processing our data

Let’s create some new columns in our yearly frame. We will add weekday, abbreviated month, day as number in the month, 4 digit year, hour of start time, and ride time in minutes.

#Create new rows in yearly frame for grouping and summarizing later
#New rows are abbreviated weekday, abbreviated month, day as number, 4 digit year, hour of start time, and ride time in minutes converted to numeric data type
trips_data <- year %>% 
  mutate(weekday = wday(started_at, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(month = month(started_at, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(day = mday(started_at)) %>% 
  mutate(year = year(started_at)) %>% 
  mutate(start_time = as.numeric(hour(started_at))) %>% 
  mutate(ride_time = as.numeric((ended_at - started_at)/60))

We will clean in up a little bit more by removing rides from “docked bikes”, rides with times less than 1 minute, and filter out rides that have no ending or starting station

#Filter rides from "docked_bikes"
#Filter rides with negative ride times
#Filter rides with no end station or start station
#Filter rides less than 1 minute for relevance
trips <- trips_data %>% 
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike") %>% 
  filter(ride_time > 1) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(end_station_id)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(start_station_id))

Analyze

Filtering and summarizing our data for graphing, and creating objects for later manipulation

#Filter and summarize trips to show mean ride times by membership status over the course of the year
by_month_member <- trips %>%
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
  group_by(month, rideable_type) %>% 
  summarize(mean_time = mean(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE), median_time = median(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE), max_time = max(ride_time), min_time = min(ride_time))
  
by_month_casual <- trips %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>% 
  group_by(month, rideable_type) %>% 
  summarize(mean_time = mean(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE), median_time = median(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE), max_time = max(ride_time), min_time = min(ride_time))

#Filter and summarize trips to show mean ride times by membership status over the course of the week
by_day_member <- trips %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
  group_by(weekday, rideable_type) %>% 
  summarize(mean_time = mean(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE), median_time = median(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE), max_time = max(ride_time), min_time = min(ride_time))

by_day_casual <- trips %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  group_by(weekday, rideable_type) %>% 
  summarize(mean_time = mean(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE), median_time = median(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE), max_time = max(ride_time), min_time = min(ride_time))

#Filter and summarize trips to show mean ride times by top 10 most popular start stations, member and casual
by_station_member <- trips %>%
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>% 
  group_by(start_station_name) %>% 
  summarise(num_rides = n(), mean_time = mean(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(num_rides)) %>% 
  slice(1:10)

by_station_casual <- trips %>%
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>% 
  group_by(start_station_name) %>% 
  summarise(num_rides = n(), mean_time = mean(ride_time, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(num_rides)) %>% 
  slice(1:10)
#Filter and summarize monthly trips to show %change month to month
monthly_rides_member <- trips %>%
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>% 
  group_by(month) %>% 
  summarize(total_rides = (n())) %>% 
  arrange(match(month, c('Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sep','Oct','Nov','Dec','Jan','Feb','Mar'))) %>% 
  mutate(MoM = (total_rides - lag(total_rides))/ lag(total_rides)) %>% 
  mutate(MoM = round(MoM * 100, 1)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(MoM))

monthly_rides_casual <- trips %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  group_by(month) %>% 
  summarize(total_rides = (n())) %>% 
  arrange(match(month, c('Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sep','Oct','Nov','Dec','Jan','Feb','Mar'))) %>% 
  mutate(MoM = (total_rides - lag(total_rides))/ lag(total_rides)) %>% 
  mutate(MoM = round(MoM * 100, 1)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(MoM))

Both bikes share a similar proportion of user type across the day. Annual Members more heavily use the service from 5 - 10 AM and from 4 - 8 PM. Casual Users see a comparative rise in ridership after 10 AM, peaking around 2 PM and drop off towards 5 PM. Act

Recommendations

Annual Members use the service more consistently and are less affected by external forces when choosing to use the service. They primarily use the service for commuting, especially during the typical “Rush Hour” 5 - 9 AM, and 4 - 6 PM. We can count on Annual Members to ride most often during these times on the weekdays and less often but still more often than the average Casual Riders. We expect Annual Members to continue using their membership during the colder months. Peak monthly ride numbers exceed 320,000 and drop to just over 100,000, a change of nearly 70%.

Casual Riders use the service less consistently but often use the bikes for longer than Annual Members. Their usage is suggested to be more recreational with peak times being the opposite of Annual Members. Their ride numbers increase the later it gets until about 5 AM, and then gain a little around lunch time. Casual Riders ride most often and for longer during the weekend and see a significant decrease in rides on weekdays. Environmental changes affect Casual Riders more than Annual Members. They ride more often and longer in the summer, and less often to a significant degree during the winter. Peak monthly ride numbers reach just over 276,000 and drop to just over 27,000, a change of 90%.

Annual Members are more often residents of Chicago and use the service for non-recreational transportation and commuting. Casual Riders are more often tourists or visiting the city and use the bikes to travel for recreation and visit attractions near the city center.
